  "prompt": "Complete an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc).?",
  "response": "Sure! Let's complete the orbital diagram for scandium (Sc), which has an atomic number of 21. This means scandium has 21 electrons. We'll distribute these electrons among the available orbitals, following the Aufbau principle, the Pauli exclusion principle, and Hund's rule.\n\nThe order of filling orbitals is: 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d.\n\n1. 1s: 2 electrons\n2. 2s: 2 electrons\n3. 2p: 6 electrons (p orbitals are split into px, py, and pz)\n4. 3s: 2 electrons\n5. 3p: 6 electrons (also split into px, py, and pz)\n6. 4s: 2 electrons\n7. 3d: 1 electron (d orbitals are split into five sub-orbitals)\n\nTherefore, the electron configuration is 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b2 3p\u2076 4s\u00b2 3d\u00b9.\n\nNow let's fill these orbitals in the diagram format. Each box represents an orbital and each arrow represents an electron:\n\n```\n1s:  \u2191\u2193\n2s:  \u2191\u2193\n2p:  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193\n3s:  \u2191\u2193\n3p:  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193\n4s:  \u2191\u2193\n3d:  \u2191\n```\n\nHere's how it is filled:\n- The 1s, 2s, 3s, and 4s orbitals each hold 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193).\n- The 2p and 3p orbitals each hold 6 electrons (each p orbital can hold 2 electrons \u2014 px, py, pz).\n- The 3d orbital starts filling after the 4s has been filled and has only 1 electron for scandium.\n\nEach electron is placed according to these principles:\n1. **Aufbau Principle:** Electrons fill orbitals starting at the lowest available energy states before filling higher states.\n2. **Pauli Exclusion Principle:** No two electrons in the same orbital can have the same set of quantum numbers; thus, one arrow must be up (\u2191) and the other down (\u2193).\n3.  **Hund's Rule:** When filling suborbitals of the same energy (like the three p orbitals or five d orbitals), one electron goes into each suborbital before any suborbital gets a second.\n\nThis completes the orbital diagram for scandium (Sc).",
